Frankincense - a resin of 

Boswellia

trees is the most precious resin religiously, socially, economically and medicinally. In an attempt to reviving its historical role in treating various chronic diseases, our group has been intensively involved in unravelling the secrets of this ancient resin. Boswellic acids and cembranoids are the major chemical constituents of frankincense with well documented medicinal properties. However, compared to boswellic acids which have been thoroughly reviewed, cembranoids have received less attention (Ahmed Al-Harrasi, Hidayat Hussain, 
Rene Csuk
, 2018; 

).

Cembranoids are naturally occurring 14-membered ring diterpenoids having interesting structural features and important biological properties. They are generated by cyclization of a geranylgeraneol derived precursor involving C-1 and C-14. The representative compound, cembrene (
1
) (
Fig. 1
) was isolated from pine oleoresin, and subsequently a large number of related compounds (cembranoids) have been reported from various terrestrial and marine organisms. 

Boswellia
species

are one of the valuable sources of these compounds (Ahmed Al-Harrasi, Hidayat Hussain, Rene Csuk, 2018; 

;

The controversy in 

Boswellia

taxonomy is huge despite the fact that only 24 species exist in this genus. This is partly due to the large chemical analyses that were based on commercial samples that lack information about the taxonomic origin (Ahmed 

; 

) but also due to the huge overlap of chemical constituents in the studied species.

