The structures of the cembranoids were settled by a detailed investigation of their conformational analysis data and spectral properties, mainly their 1D and 2D NMR and high-resolution mass spectral data (
Table 3
). Some routine chemical transformations of certain cembranoids, such as serratol, were carried out to characterize the molecules (RS Pardhy, SC Bhattacharyya, 1978; 

). The X-ray crystallographic analysis has also been utilized to confirm the structures of several complex cembranoids. Some conformational studies of several cembranoids have also been reported (

). It is noteworthy mentioning that we were unable to find a supporting evidence that any of the reported compounds is an artefact. Having said that, it is not unexpected to see artifacts given the common intramolecular opening of epoxyalcohols and the expected Payne rearrangement of α- hydroxyepoxides, however, we relied solely on the published data. A careful chromatographic isolation of these compounds should be performed to prove or disprove this fact.

Due to the fact that the absolute stereochemistry of C–1S has been unambiguously confirmed by X-ray analysis for the similar compound incensole oxide ( 8 ) (
) as well as by CD spectroscopy of Serratol ( 14 ) (
), the enantiomeric assignment for isoincensole oxide ( 12) ( Fig. 3 ) as rel (1 S , 7 R , 8 S , 11 S , 12 R ) should be preferred (
). This fact is supported by NOESY spectra that revealed cis arrangement of the isopropyl group with Me-20. This is, however, in contrast with Kato’ s proposal (
) who suggested the E configuration. The NOE between H-15 and Me-20 confirms the cis arrangement of the isopropyl group and Me-20 (1S, 12R). Kato et al. proposed the configuration of C-11 as S due to the lack of NOE interactions between H-11 and Me-20. However, based on the molecular models proposed by Greve el al. (
), this NOE should theoretically exist and it was interestingly seen in the NOESY experiment. It is therefore concluded that the stereochemistry at C-11 is confirmed as S . The lack of NOE interactions between H-7 and Me-19 indicates that these two groups are in trans position to each other. Furthermore,
concluded that the stereochemistry of 7 R , 8 S attributed to a downfield shift of the olefinic proton when compared with the 7 S , 8 S epimer but they haven’ t compared it with the other diastereomer 7 S , 8 R . Greve et al. detected clear NOEs between H-3 and H-6a as well as between H-7 and H-13a in their NOESY experiment which further support the rel (1S,7S,8R,11S, 12R) configuration. Therefore, the stereochemistry of isoincensole oxide ( 12) is as proposed by
, and adopted here.

