Various chemical modifications and syntheses of cembranoids of 

Boswellia
species

have been carried out. These synthetic studies were accomplished mainly involving incensole and incensole acetate along with some other cembranoids. The results have been discussed in some earlier reports (Ahmed 

; 

).

Biosynthesis of cembranoids has been discussed by various researchers (Ahmed
;
; McMillan. J, 1999). Four steps are involved in the biogenesis of cembranoids. The first step is the formation of the isoprene unit through two different pathways, starting from 1-deoxyxylulose or mevalonic acid. The combination of the isoprene units results in the generation of geranylgeranyl pyrophosphate (GGPP) (isoprenoid) in the second step. Later, in the third step, cyclization of GGPP occurs via a carbenium ion to form the cembranoid core structure. Finally, in the fourth step functionalization (e.g. oxidation; hydroxylation etc.) of the skeleton of cembranoids takes place to form the various naturally occurring cembranoids (Scheme 3).

